# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apfelküchle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apfelküchle/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apfelküchle/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apfelküchle/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apfelküchle/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apfelküchle/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apfelküchle/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apfelküchle/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:apfelküchle/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:apfelküchle/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Its colour, juice content, sweetness, and overall flavour have made the Ambrosia one of the most purchased apples in numerous countries.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia apple tree has an upright growth pattern, varying on soil quality, rootstock, environment, and management.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] The tree develops lateral branches, requiring pruning to maintain vigour and fruit size.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] In the first two years of growth, significant tree training is needed to assure well-angled fruiting branches and productivity.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apple trees are suitable for dense planting, have high yields, and require little pruning during the winter.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Pollinating partners of the Ambrosia include the Cortland, Fuji, and Granny Smith.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] The fruit is medium to large, 6.8–7.5 cm (2.7–3.0 in) in diameter, weighing about 215 grams (0.474 lb), and has mostly red, glossy colouration, with yellow patches.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] It has cream-coloured, firm, and juicy texture, with a mild and sweet flavour reminiscent of pear and low acidity, with the flesh resisting oxidation, making it suitable for salads and fresh fruit displays.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] These apples flower in the mid-to-late blossom period, and are harvested in mid-to-late season (mid-September in its native Similkameen Valley of British Columbia; September–October in Ontario, mid-October in Quebec).
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apples produce a low amount of ethylene, not displaying the usual climacteric rise at harvest.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Accordingly, internal ethylene concentrations do not indicate accurate fruit maturity, whereas skin colour and starch staining charts are commonly used for optimal harvest and standardization of fruit quality.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Orchard irrigation conditions appear to be a factor causing soft scald and reduced quality of Ambrosia apples during storage.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Derived from a chance seedling, the Ambrosia is suspected to be a cross of the Starking Delicious and the Golden Delicious because those apples existed in the orchard where the Ambrosia was discovered growing.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is a "club" variety of apple, in which a cultivar is patented by an organization that sets quality standards and provides marketing, while production is limited to club members.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Centralized control allowed limitation of color variation to pink/red, as the variety would colour differently in warmer climates.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] The patent expired in Canada in 2015, in the United States in 2017, and in Chile in 2021.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] It remains active in many other countries until as late as 2034.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in Canada, the Mennell family obtained plant breeders rights, and all growers were allowed, paying a royalty of CA$2–3.75 per tree planting.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in the US, growers paid the lesser of US$1 per tree planting or US$1,000 per acre, and a US$1,000 franchise fee.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia Gold is marketed as the premium version of this variety.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is most commonly cultivated in British Columbia, where it was the third most-produced apple in 2016.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] By the mid 2020s, British Columbia continues to take the lead in production, followed by Ontario and Nova Scotia.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] Alongside the Honeycrisp and Gala, the Ambrosia has risen in prominence among Canadian farmers and consumers at the expense of the Red Delicious.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] In the United States, the majority of Ambrosia apples are harvested in Washington State and New York.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] This variety is also grown in Chile, New Zealand, the Netherlands, and Italy, among other countries.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] In the early 21st century, it is one of the most popular apple varieties in Canada and the United States, especially in the South and Midwest.
[src:apfelküchle/ambrosia-apple] It has also found success in the Asian market, notably Vietnam.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] The **Apfelküchle** is a traditional German pastry, consisting of sliced apples dipped in batter and fried to a golden-brown color.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] It is popular in Baden-Württemberg, a federal state in southern Germany.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] The Apfelküchle has spread throughout Europe and the US.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] It is similar to an apple fritter but is made more like a pancake, and can be prepared in several ways.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] While it is traditionally eaten as a complete meal, because of its sweet taste, Apfelküchle has also become popular as a dessert.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] The word Apfelküchle consists of two words: *Apfel*, meaning apple, and *Küchle*, a diminutive in Swabian German of *Kuchen*, meaning cake.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] A possible translation is *little apple pie*.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] It is not completely certain when Apfelküchle were first made, however it is known that the pastry was created in south-west Germany in the state of Baden-Württemberg, where it has been a long-standing traditional meal.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Recently, Apfelküchle has spread beyond Germany's borders and has become very popular.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Apples do not tend to tolerate long storage through the colder seasons.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Making Apfelküchle is a way to use the spare apples picked in the summer and early autumn.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] A large number of apples that would otherwise be wasted or were slightly damaged before they could be eaten (either en route to the vendor or damaged during harvest), can be used to make Apfelküchle.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Apfelküchle is traditionally eaten in Baden-Württemberg on Fat Thursday, the Thursday prior to Rose Monday (Carnival Monday), similar to eating paczki on Fat Tuesday.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Apfelküchle is traditionally eaten as a main course, however in recent years it has often been served as a dessert.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] During Carnival, the Apfelküchle is a must.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] It is also part of every religious holiday in southern Germany.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] There are a few different ways to make Apfelküchle.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Most recipes differ mainly in minor ingredients, which are swapped out based on personal taste.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Apfelküchle all have a main ingredient of apples and dough (made from eggs, flour, sugar, salt, and milk).
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Different variations of dough can be made by adding extras such as beer, fruit brandy, and cinnamon.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Since the end of the 18th century, it has become common to use a variety of sauces to refine dishes in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] As a popular dish in that area, Apfelküchle is often served with its own variety of sauces and sides.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] The most common way to eat Apfelküchle is warm with cinnamon and sugar, or dusted with powdered sugar.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] One of the most popular refinements is to serve it cold with a vanilla sauce.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] It is also popular, especially among children, to serve Apfelküchle with vanilla ice cream.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Cooks in Baden-Württemberg also like to flambé it with Grand Marnier or rum and serve it with a little scoop of vanilla ice cream.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] Another sauce used to dress Apfelküchle is *Chaudeausauce*, a French term for hot water, which is composed mainly of wine, vinegar, lemon juice, egg yolks and sugar.
[src:apfelküchle/apfelküchle] It is traditionally made with white wine; usually champagne, and occasionally with a shot of cognac or sherry.
